<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06242228 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06242228 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  BICYCLE; DESIGN; CHANGE; GUIDELINE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Want to upgrade your cycling equipment without spending a lot of money? KeithBontrager's partner at Bontrager Cycles, Hans Heim, offers the followingsuggestions:; (box) Make sure your bike is property adjusted to your body. Payspecial attention to all the &quot;contact&quot; points, like the seat, pedals and handgrips. &quot;Your enjoyment of the sport will be greatly enhanced and the bikewon't end up sitting in the garage if it's properly adjusted,&quot; Heim said.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Venture  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  EASY WAYS TO UPGRADE YOUR BIKE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related article on this page.  </MEMO><TEXT>     (box) Use the appropriate tires for the kind of riding you do. Wide, knobbytires provide good traction off-road. Narrow, high-pressure tires work best onthe pavement.;   (box) Replace heavy rims with lighter ones. &quot;Wheel upgradingprovides the greatest benefit for the money involved,&quot; Heim said.;   (box)Invest in a pair of cycling shoes. The stiff soles distribute pedaling forcemore efficiently than flexible, rubber-soled shoes. &quot;It's like someoneturbo-charged your car,&quot; Heim said.;   (box) Get a pair of cycling shorts.They'll keep you comfortable on long rides so you can pay attention to otherthings.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  -- Terri Morgan  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910829  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7G  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  182  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday, August 29, 199100242228,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>